The content of a static `style.css` file typically consists of CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) code that defines the visual styling and layout of an HTML document.

Here's a basic example of what you might find in a `style.css` file:

```css
/* 
    Global Styles
*/

/* Reset default browser styles */
* {
    box-sizing: border-box;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
}

body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    font-size: 16px;
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: #333;
    background-color: #f9f9f9;
}

/* 
    Component Styles
*/

.header {
    background-color: #333;
    color: #fff;
    padding: 20px;
    text-align: center;
}

.header.logo {
    margin-bottom: 10px;
}

.navbar {
    background-color: #333;
    padding: 10px;
}

/* 
    Typography Styles
*/

h1 {
    font-size: 24px;
    color: #666;
}

h2, h3 {
    font-size: 18px;
    color: #444;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
}

/* 
    Link Styles
*/

a {
    text-decoration: none;
    color: #337ab7;
}

a:hover {
    color: #23527c;
}

/* 
    Button Styles
*/

button {
    background-color: #337ab7;
    color: #fff;
    padding: 10px 20px;
    border: none;
    border-radius: 5px;
    cursor: pointer;
}

button:hover {
    background-color: #23527c;
}
```

