Here's a simple Lit component that displays the number of clicks:

```typescript
import { html, LitElement, property } from 'lit-element';

class ClickCounter extends LitElement {
  @property({ type: Number }) clickCount = 0;

  render() {
    return html`
      <button @click=${this.handleClick}>Clicks: ${this.clickCount}</button>
    `;
  }

  handleClick() {
    this.clickCount += 1;
  }
}

customElements.define('click-counter', ClickCounter);
```

To use this component in your app, you can then import it and add it to your app's HTML:

```html
<lit-element-app>
  <click-counter></click-counter>
</lit-element-app>
```

When the user clicks the button, the `handleClick` method is called. It increments the `clickCount` property, which is then displayed in the button's label through Lit's template literals feature.

Note: This code is written according to the LitElement guidelines and uses Lit's modern syntax for writing templates and handling properties. The `@property` decorator is used to make the `clickCount` property observable, which allows the component to automatically update its template whenever the `clickCount` changes.

Also, note that LitElement requires a main application or a host element for it to work, that's why I wrapped the `click-counter` element in a lit-element-app tag.

Here's a corrected Lit component that counts how many times it has been clicked and displays that:

```typescript
import { html, LitElement, property } from 'lit-element';

class ClickCounter extends LitElement {
  static styles = [html`
    :host {
      display: inline-block;
    }
  `];

  @property({ type: Number }) clickCount = 0;

  render() {
    return html`
      <button @click=${this.handleClick}>Clicks: ${this.clickCount}</button>
    `;
  }

  handleClick() {
    this.clickCount += 1;
  }
}

customElements.define('click-counter', ClickCounter);
```

In this Lit component, the rendering of the button is done directly in the Lit's template function (`render()` method), and each time the button is clicked, the `handleClick` method is called which increments the `clickCount` property and the template will automatically update.

Here's a sample JavaScript code snippet that compares two strings and outputs their identical and differing parts:

```javascript
function compareStrings(string1, string2) {
    let identicalPart = '';
    let differingPart1 = '';
    let differingPart2 = '';

    let maxLength = Math.max(string1.length, string2.length);

    for (let i = 0; i < maxLength; i++) {
        if (i < string1.length && i < string2.length) {
            if (string1[i] === string2[i]) {
                identicalPart += string1[i];
            } else {
                if (differingPart1 === '') {
                    differingPart1 += string1[i];
                }
                if (differingPart2 === '') {
                    differingPart2 += string2[i];
                } else {
                    differingPart1 += '<' + string1[i] + '>';
                    differingPart2 += '<' + string2[i] + '>';
                }
            }
        } else if (i < string1.length) {
            differingPart1 += string1[i];
        } else {
            differingPart2 += string2[i];
        }
    }

    return {
        identicalPart: identicalPart,
        differingPart1: differingPart1,
        differingPart2: differingPart2,
    };
}

// Test the function
let string1 = 'Hello, World!';
let string2 = 'Hi, World!';
let result = compareStrings(string1, string2);

console.log('Identical part:', result.identicalPart);
console.log('Differing part in string1:', result.differingPart1);
console.log('Differing part in string2:', result.differingPart2);
```

This script compares two input strings character by character and outputs the parts where they are identical and the parts where they differ.

When it encounters a character that is different in the two strings, it marks the differing parts in string1 and string2 by surrounding them with angle brackets. If a string is shorter than the other, it fills in the remaining characters with a differing mark.

