Here's the updated code that prints the Longest Common Subsequence (LCS) string:

```java
class Solution {
    public String longestCommonSubsequence(String text1, String text2) {
        int n = text1.length();
        int m = text2.length();

        // Initialize memoization table
        int[][] memo = new int[n + 1][m + 1];

        // Initialize result string
        StringBuilder lcsString = new StringBuilder();

        // Fill memoization table
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            for (int j = 1; j <= m; j++) {
                if (text1.charAt(i - 1) == text2.charAt(j - 1)) {
                    memo[i][j] = memo[i - 1][j - 1] + 1;
                } else {
                    memo[i][j] = Math.max(memo[i - 1][j], memo[i][j - 1]);
                }
            }
        }

        // Backtrack to construct the LCS string
        int i = n;
        int j = m;
        while (i > 0 && j > 0) {
            if (text1.charAt(i - 1) == text2.charAt(j - 1)) {
                lcsString.insert(0, text1.charAt(i - 1));
                i--;
                j--;
            } else if (memo[i - 1][j] > memo[i][j - 1]) {
                i--;
            } else {
                j--;
            }
        }

        return lcsString.toString();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Solution solution = new Solution();
        String text1 = "AGGTAB";
        String text2 = "GXTXAYB";
        System.out.println("LCS string: " + solution.longestCommonSubsequence(text1, text2));
    }
}
```

In this code, I made the following changes:

* I replaced the `dfs` method with a bottom-up dynamic programming approach to fill the memoization table.
* I added a `StringBuilder` to store the LCS string character by character.
* I added a `while` loop to backtrack and construct the LCS string.
* I updated the main method to print the LCS string.

