Note that the HTML template (`internet_status.html`) would display 'Connecting...' by default, because checking internet status every 5 seconds would not update this template frequently. But, this would be constantly updating in the console.

To continuously monitor internet connectivity without needing to refresh the page, you can use JavaScript (specifically, the WebSocket protocol) to update the webpage in real-time based on the Flask API's current internet status.

Here's the modified Flask API to achieve this:

```python
from flask import Flask, render_template, jsonify
import urllib.request
import time
import threading

app = Flask(__name__)
last_status = 'Connecting...'

def check_internet():
    global last_status
    while True:
        try:
            urllib.request.urlopen('https://www.google.com')
            last_status = 'Connected'
        except:
            last_status = 'Not Connected'
        time.sleep(5)  # Check every 5 seconds

@app.route('/')
def internet_status():
    return render_template('internet_status.html', status=last_status)

@app.route('/status')
def status_api():
    return jsonify({'status': last_status})

if __name__ == '__main__':
    thr = threading.Thread(target=check_internet)
    thr.daemon = True  # So that thread stops when main program stops
    thr.start()
    app.run(debug=False)  # Do not use debug mode when running in production
```

