Here is a simple C# method that checks if a string is a palindrome:
```csharp
/// <summary>
/// Checks if a string is a palindrome.
/// A palindrome is a string that reads the same forwards and backwards.
/// </summary>
/// <param name="input">The string to check.</param>
/// <returns>True if the string is a palindrome, false otherwise.</returns>
public static bool IsPalindrome(string input)
{
    // Remove any non-alphanumeric characters and convert to lowercase
    var cleanedInput = new string(input.Where(c => char.IsLetterOrDigit(c)).ToArray()).ToLower();

    // Compare the cleaned string with its reverse
    return cleanedInput.SequenceEqual(cleanedInput.Reverse());
}
```
Here's an explanation of how the method works:

1. The method uses LINQ to remove any non-alphanumeric characters from the input string and convert it to lowercase. This is done using the `Where` method to filter out non-alphanumeric characters and the `ToLower` method to convert to lowercase.
2. The method then uses the `SequenceEqual` method to compare the cleaned string with its reverse. The `Reverse` method returns a sequence of characters in reverse order, which is then compared with the original cleaned string.

You can use this method like this:
```csharp
string input = "A man, a plan, a canal: Panama";
bool isPalindrome = IsPalindrome(input);
Console.WriteLine(isPalindrome); // Output: True
```
Note that this method has a time complexity of O(n), where n is the length of the input string. This is because it uses LINQ to create a new string and then compares it with its reverse.

Here's an updated version of the method that ignores any non-alphanumeric characters:
```csharp
/// <summary>
/// Checks if a string is a palindrome, ignoring non-alphanumeric characters.
/// A palindrome is a string that reads the same forwards and backwards.
/// </summary>
/// <param name="input">The string to check.</param>
/// <returns>True if the string is a palindrome, false otherwise.</returns>
public static bool IsPalindrome(string input)
{
    // Remove any non-alphanumeric characters and convert to lowercase
    var cleanedInput = new string(input.Where(c => char.IsLetterOrDigit(c)).ToArray()).ToLower();

    // Compare the cleaned string with its reverse
    return cleanedInput.SequenceEqual(cleanedInput.Reverse());
}
```
This method works exactly the same as the previous version, but the LINQ query `input.Where(c => char.IsLetterOrDigit(c))` now removes any non-alphanumeric characters from the input string before comparing it with its reverse.

However, please note that the `SequenceEqual` method has to iterate over the entire string twice (once for the original string and once for the reversed string), which could be inefficient for very large strings.

If you want a more efficient solution, you can use two pointers, one at the beginning and one at the end of the string, and work your way towards the center. Here's an example:
```csharp
public static bool IsPalindrome(string input)
{
    // Remove any non-alphanumeric characters and convert to lowercase
    int left = 0, right = input.Length - 1;
    while (left < right)
    {
        if (!char.IsLetterOrDigit(input[left])) left++;
        else if (!char.IsLetterOrDigit(input[right])) right--;
        else if (input[left].ToString().ToLower()!= input[right].ToString().ToLower())
            return false;
        else
        {
            left++;
            right--;
        }
    }

    // If the loop finishes without finding any differences, the string is a palindrome
    return true;
}
```
This method has a time complexity of O(n), where n is the length of the input string, but it only iterates over the string once.

Here's a simple function that can parse URL query string parameters in TypeScript without using the Window or Document API. We will use a library called `query-string`. You'll need to install it using npm or yarn:

```bash
npm install query-string
```

```typescript
import { parse } from 'query-string';

function getQueryParams(url: string): { [key: string]: string[] } {
    const parsedUrl = new URL(url);
    const queryParams: { [key: string]: string[] } = {};

    // parse the query string
    const queryString = parsedUrl.search.substring(1);
    const parsedQueryString = query_string.parse(queryString);

    // convert the query string params to a readable object
    Object.keys(parsedQueryString).forEach((key) => {
        if (!queryParams[key]) {
            queryParams[key] = [];
        }
        queryParams[key].push(parsedQueryString[key]);
    });

    return queryParams;
}

// Example usage
const url = 'https://example.com/path?a=1&a=2&b=3';
console.log(getQueryParams(url));  // Output: { a: [ '1', '2' ], b: [ '3' ] }
```

Keep in mind that the `query-string` library is just used here for parsing, and we don't need a full import for the type definition of it, this above code snippet has used the type for the explanation. The function itself only uses the `URL` class which is part of the JavaScript API and does not require any extra import. 

However if we were to implement this function purely manually (without using the `URL` class), here's how we would do it:

```typescript
function getQueryParams(url: string): { [key: string]: string[] } {
    const queryParams: { [key: string]: string[] } = {};

    const queryStringStart = url.indexOf('?');
    if (queryStringStart!== -1) {
        const queryString = url.substring(queryStringStart + 1);
        const queryParts = queryString.split('&');

        queryParts.forEach((part) => {
            const [key, value] = part.split('=');
            if (!queryParams[key]) {
                queryParams[key] = [];
            }
            queryParams[key].push(value);
        });
    }

    return queryParams;
}
```

This function manually finds the start of the query string, splits it into individual query parameters, and then parses each parameter into a key-value pair. The resulting object is returned.

Here's a function to parse URL query string parameters without using `URL` class or `URLSearchParams`:

```typescript
function getQueryParams(url: string): { [key: string]: string[] } {
    const queryParams: { [key: string]: string[] } = {};

    const queryStringStart = url.indexOf('?');
    if (queryStringStart!== -1) {
        const queryString = url.substring(queryStringStart + 1);
        const queryParts = queryString.split('&');

        queryParts.forEach((part) => {
            const partStart = part.indexOf('=');
            if (partStart!== -1) {
                const key = part.substring(0, partStart);
                const value = part.substring(partStart + 1);
                if (!queryParams[key]) {
                    queryParams[key] = [];
                }
                queryParams[key].push(value);
            } else {
                const key = part;
                if (!queryParams[key]) {
                    queryParams[key] = [];
                }
                queryParams[key].push('');
            }
        });
    }

    return queryParams;
}

