System.Text.Json is a high-performance JSON serializer and deserializer provided by the.NET Core framework. To deserialize a list of objects, you can use the following code:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Text.Json;
using System.Text.Json.Serialization;

public class YourObject
{
    public string Property1 { get; set; }
    public string Property2 { get; set; }
}

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        // Define the JSON string
        string json = @"[
            {
                ""Property1"": ""Value1"",
                ""Property2"": ""Value2""
            },
            {
                ""Property1"": ""Value3"",
                ""Property2"": ""Value4""
            }
        ]";

        // Deserialize the JSON string into a list of objects
        var options = new JsonSerializerOptions { PropertyNameCaseInsensitive = true };
        var list = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<List<YourObject>>(json, options);

        // Print the deserialized list to the console
        foreach (var obj in list)
        {
            Console.WriteLine($"Property1: {obj.Property1}, Property2: {obj.Property2}");
        }
    }
}
```

In the code above, the `JsonSerializerOptions` object is used to configure the deserialization, including making the property names case-insensitive. The `Deserialize` method is then used to deserialize the JSON string into a list of `YourObject` objects.

Note that the `PropertyNameCaseInsensitive` option is not necessary if you're using camelCase or PascalCase properties in your JSON string.

You can change `YourObject` to whatever class you need to deserialize from the JSON string.

Also, you can use `JsonSerializer.DeserializeAsync` to deserialize JSON strings asynchronously.

