Based on your previous error with `eax` and `addb`, and now with `rax` and `l` suffix, it seems like the issue is due to the fact that you're missing operand numbers or flags in the assembly directives.

Here's a corrected example for `addb` instruction using `eax`:

```c
asm ("addb %%al, (%1)");
```

In this example, `%%al` is the low byte of `eax`, and `(%1)` is the address of the memory location to add to `al`. 

And here's a corrected example for `addl` instruction using `rax`:

```c
asm ("addl %%ebx, %0");
```

In this example, `%%ebx` is the second operand, and `%0` is the first operand, which is the value of `rax`.

Here's how to use these corrected `asm` directives in your code:

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int x = 5, y = 2;
    int result;

    asm ("movl %%ebx, %0" : "=r" (result) : "r" (y) : "%ebx");
    printf("Value of y: %d\n", y);

    asm ("addl %%ebx, %0" : "=r" (result) : "r" (result), "r" (y) : "%ebx");
    printf("Result after addition: %d\n", result);

    return 0;
}
```

Please note that inline assembly can be specific to the platform you're compiling on, and the syntax and available registers may differ between compilers and platforms.

You want to create a view model abstract class that can work with any concrete state data class, so you can reuse it across different cases. This is a great approach to follow the principle of Don't Repeat Yourself (DRY).

Here's a suggestion:

Create an abstract `StateDataViewModel` class that takes an `IStateData` interface as a dependency. This way, you can define the view model's responsibilities without coupling it to a specific concrete state data class.

```csharp
// Define an interface for state data
public interface IStateData
{
    // Properties and methods common to all state data classes
}

// Concrete state data class example (MyStateData)
public class MyStateData : IStateData
{
    public int State { get; set; } // example property
}

public abstract class StateDataViewModel<TStateData> where TStateData : IStateData
{
    private TStateData _stateData;

    protected StateDataViewModel(TStateData stateData)
    {
        _stateData = stateData;
    }

    // Properties and methods that rely on IStateData properties and methods

    public int DataValue
    {
        get { return _stateData.State; }
        set { _stateData.State = value; }
    }

    // Other view model responsibilities...
}

// Use the view model with MyStateData
public class MyStateDataViewModel : StateDataViewModel<MyStateData>
{
    public MyStateDataViewModel(MyStateData stateData) : base(stateData)
    {
    }
}
```

By using generics and an interface, you've decoupled the view model from the specific concrete state data class, making it possible to reuse the `StateDataViewModel` with different state data classes, like `MyStateData2`, `YourStateData`, and so on.

Remember to define the `IStateData` interface with the common properties and methods used by your various state data classes. This will ensure that the view model can work seamlessly with any concrete class implementing the interface.

