To ensure that your queries are already fetched on the server with T3stack version 10, you can use the `client.fetch` method or the `onMutate` callback.

Here's an example:

**Method 1: Using `client.fetch`**

```javascript
import { useQuery, client } from '@t3-stack/core';

const query = gql`
  query SomeQuery {
   ...
  }
`;

useQuery({
  query,
  client: client.fetch, // fetch data on server side
});
```

However, this approach isn't recommended because `client.fetch` refetches data on every render, which can lead to performance issues.

**Method 2: Using `onMutate`**

```javascript
import { useQuery, useMutation } from '@t3-stack/core';

const query = gql`
  query SomeQuery {
   ...
  }
`;

const { data, mutate, isMutating } = useMutation({
  mutation: query,
  onMutate: (variables) => {
    if (!isServer() ||!isClient()) return;
    const cachedData = useQuery({ query });
    const newVariables = useQuery({ query }, { variables });
    if (cachedData!== null && JSON.stringify(cachedData) === JSON.stringify(newVariables)) {
      // Data was already fetched on the server, you can skip refetching
      console.log("Data was already fetched!");
    } else {
      // Data was not fetched on the server, refetch it
      mutate({ variables });
    }
  },
});
```

In this example, we use the `onMutate` callback to check if the data was already fetched on the server. If it was, we skip refetching it.

**Note**: This approach requires you to be on a server-rendered page (e.g., `onServer` mode in Next.js), otherwise, it won't work correctly.

Alternatively, you can use the `isServer` hook from `@t3-stack/core` to check if you're on a server-rendered page. If you're on a server-rendered page, you can safely assume that your data was already fetched on the server.

```javascript
import { isServer, useQuery } from '@t3-stack/core';

if (isServer) {
  // Data was already fetched on the server, you can skip refetching
  console.log("Data was already fetched!");
}
```

