You want to fetch an image from a URL, convert it to a binary file, and then send it to an API in an Angular application.

To achieve this, you can use the Angular HttpClient to fetch the image, convert it to a binary file using the `Blob` API, and finally send it to the API using the `HttpClient.post()` method.

Here's a sample code snippet to help you get started:

```typescript
import { Component, OnInit } from '@angular/core';
import { HttpClient } from '@angular/common/http';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-example',
  template: '<p>Example</p>'
})
export class ExampleComponent implements OnInit {
  private apiUrl = 'your-api-url.com'; // API URL to send the image
  private image_url = 'https://example.com/image.jpg'; // URL of the image

  constructor(private http: HttpClient) { }

  ngOnInit(): void {
    this.downloadImageAndSend();
  }

  downloadImageAndSend(): void {
    this.http.get(this.image_url, { responseType: 'blob' })
     .subscribe(response => {
        const blob = new Blob([response], { type: 'image/jpeg' });
        const formData = new FormData();
        formData.append('image', blob);

        this.http.post(this.apiUrl, formData)
         .subscribe(res => {
            console.log(res);
          }, error => {
            console.error(error);
          });
      }, () => {
        console.error('Failed to download the image');
      });
  }
}
```

In the above code:

1.  We use the `http.get()` method to fetch the image from the provided URL. We set `responseType` to `'blob'` to retrieve the image as a binary file.
2.  We create a new `Blob` object with the downloaded binary data.
3.  We create a new form data object and append the binary image data to it.
4.  We use the `http.post()` method to send the image data to the API along with the form data.

Please replace `'your-api-url.com'` with your actual API URL and `'https://example.com/image.jpg'` with the actual URL of the image.

Make sure to adjust the API endpoint and the data you're sending according to your specific requirements.

